  "prompt": "How do you stop a sunburn from peeling?",
  "response": "Dealing with a sunburn can be uncomfortable, and preventing peeling is often a concern. Here are some steps you can take to help reduce the likelihood of peeling:\n\n1. **Cool Down Your Skin:**\n   - Take cool showers or baths to soothe the burn.\n   - Apply cool compresses to the affected area.\n\n2. **Hydrate:**\n   - Drink plenty of water to keep your skin hydrated from the inside out.\n\n3. **Moisturize:**\n   - Use a gentle, fragrance-free moisturizer or aloe vera gel to keep the skin hydrated.\n   - Apply moisturizer several times a day.\n\n4. **Avoid Further Sun Exposure:**\n   - Stay out of the sun, especially during peak hours (10 a.m. to 4 p.m.).\n   - Wear protective clothing and use sunscreen with a high SPF.\n\n5. **Use Over-the-Counter Treatments:**\n   - Consider using over-the-counter hydrocortisone cream to reduce inflammation and itching.\n   - Avoid products containing alcohol or benzocaine, which can irritate the skin.\n\n6. **Do Not Pick or Peel:**\n   - Resist the urge to peel off the skin. This can lead to infection and slow down the healing process.\n\n7. **Stay Gentle:**\n   - Avoid harsh soaps and scrubbing the affected area.\n   - Pat your skin dry after bathing rather than rubbing it.\n\n8. **Consider Pain Relief:**\n   - Take an over-the-counter pain reliever like ibuprofen or acetaminophen to help reduce pain and inflammation.\n\nRemember that sunburn is a sign of skin damage, and prevention is key. In the future, always use sunscreen, wear protective clothing, and limit sun exposure to avoid sunburn. If the sunburn is severe, or if you experience symptoms such as blisters, fever, or chills, seek medical attention.",
